00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.120
And as you can imagine, these get a lot of 
traffic and we need to make sure that they

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:19.840
are as accessible and and welcoming 
as possible to everyone who visits.

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:29.440
A few years ago, um the World Accessibility Day 
New England Conference was held at the university.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.280
Pretty much everyone from our 
office's web team attended.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:40.080
As the conference went on, it became very obvious, 
very quickly, how much work we needed to do.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:45.680
One of the things we looked at on our 
sites, was the main navigation components.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:52.400
As a state institution, we had some pretty 
specific requirements. For instance, I think

00:02:52.400 --> 00:03:00.240
that at the time we were still supporting Internet 
Explorer 10 and we also wanted to make sure that

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:07.920
for instance, people could use the navigation 
elements without JavaScript and we wanted to

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:14.800
make sure that we were in compliance with all 
the relevant state and federal laws. And we also

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:21.760
wanted to do the right thing and have our websites 
be as good as they could be. So one of the things

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:27.200
after that conference was, I wanted to improve 
these navigational elements which leads us here

00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:35.200
today. Now I'd like to point out that this project 
and presentation are based on the majority of the

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:41.440
needs for sites currently in use at the University 
of Connecticut. So even if you choose not to use

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:48.000
the specific approach I'll show you, the basic 
ideas can be adapted to a wide range of sites.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:55.360
Now unless you're building a site which is 
only one page, people are going to have to find

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:02.960
their way around and not only that, but as a web 
developer I know that if I put something or really

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:10.720
anything interactive on a site, people are going 
to try and use it. So that means interactive

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:19.280
elements may get used in ways that are unexpected 
or unfamiliar to me. As developers, just like

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:25.440
we validate forum inputs, because we can't 
anticipate every single thing someone might enter,

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:33.200
we need to consider how people will use our 
sites besides with a mouse and screen. In terms

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:40.960
of accessibility, this concept applies to visitors 
with permanent disabilities first and foremost. At

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:47.840
the same time, some visitors may have a temporary 
or contextual accessibility need with respect to

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:53.920
a site. Their mouse might break, they might be 
working on an airplane going through turbulence,

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:59.840
their dominant hand might be broken or maybe 
they visited an eye doctor and got their pupils

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:06.560
dilated, we just can't know. We can't know the 
situation for every single person who visits us,

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:14.080
but we can try to design, build and prepare 
sites in the most equitable ways we can.

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:19.680
So how can we make sure this happens?
Well we try to keep our sites POUR.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:25.360
You may have heard or seen 
this acronym POUR in the past,

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:32.560
but what does it mean in the context of a 
navigation menu? In my view, Perceivable

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:40.160
means if a visitor can physically see the menu, 
it must be visible or be able to be made visible.

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:47.280
If that visitor can't physically see the menu, a 
screen reader should detect and announce items.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:55.680
For the menu to be Operable, someone should be 
able to interact with it, with the mouse and

00:05:55.680 --> 00:06:04.000
or the keyboard. If someone uses a mouse and there 
are sub-menus, they need to be resilient. That is,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.640
the sub-menus can't disappear immediately.
Further, all the items in a sub-menu need to

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:18.320
be reachable with a mouse or a keyboard. For the 
menu to be Understandable, it should behave in a

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:26.720
predictable way. Therefore, it needs to maintain 
visual and auditory consistency. For instance,

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:32.640
if an icon toggles between two states, such as 
open and closed, it should do that predictably.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:38.960
Menu items should announce themselves in a 
predictable way for people who use screen readers.

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:46.720
Finally for the menu to be Robust, in our 
case, we wanted to ensure that it would work

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:53.520
at least to some degree without JavaScript 
and this meant keeping the style, the

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:59.040
the style and user experience approximately the 
same, as if there were JavaScript available.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:04.080
In order to accomplish these goals, we identified

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:09.600
three cases for menu items that are 
typical for the types of site we build.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:18.960
Overall, I think these cases are pretty 
common. First a link by itself which we

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:25.200
can easily rely on WordPress to handle. After 
that we identified two types of sub-menus.

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:32.240
Those that have a link to a top level page with 
sub-pages beneath and menu items that need to be,

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:39.840
and menu items that need to solely act 
as a toggle to a series of sub-items.

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:47.760
These are fairly typical types of elements in 
a nav menu. Either you want to go somewhere by

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:53.440
following a link, or you want to reveal more 
choices through some kind of toggling action.

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:59.360
So now that we've got our goals 
through the POUR acronym and our cases,

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:04.320
we need to have a good idea of what 
elements are available to build with.

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:12.240
So before we try to style anything or provide 
interaction, we need to get a handle on the

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:17.840
HTML tags and properties we want and how 
they're going to get rendered to the page.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:26.720
This actually has a massive impact on the 
overall, all the decisions that get made later.

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:33.120
For instance, the style, JavaScript, everything 
else that comes after. If we don't have a good

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:40.160
concept of what we have at the beginning and where 
we're trying to go, then we won't be able to add

00:08:40.160 --> 00:08:49.600
on. Fortunately, WordPress has a built-in way to 
generate a menu with the wp_nav_menu function.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:58.720
And I'm sure that many of you are familiar 
with this.The good news is that wp_ nav_menu

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:05.360
is easy to use and get started with. It accepts 
a list of arguments that provide a fair amount

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:12.400
of customization quickly and then after that, 
as soon as the page loads, it displays a menu.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:20.960
One argument which I tend to change immediately, 
is the container argument. By default,

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:27.280
the menu will be contained by a div. This 
isn't ideal for a navigation menu of this type,

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:34.720
because a div doesn't impart any structure 
or meeting on its own, but you can set the

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:42.000
container to a nav element. When you do this the 
final output of the menu will be wrapped in a nav

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:50.720
tag. Browsers will then detect the tag and create 
an implicit ARIA role for it, with a landmark.This

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:56.880
is a useful accessibility improvement, because 
a screen reader will have an easier time

00:09:56.880 --> 00:10:04.160
parsing the document's content. There are other 
arguments which you may be familiar with as well.

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:10.960
For instance, you can set custom classes or 
IDs or set a theme location. Depending on

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:15.360
how many navigation sections you 
have on the page, you might also

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:22.080
set the container, or ARIA label argument as 
well, to further clarify the menu's purpose.

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:31.520
Now wp_nav_menu works really well for menus 
that have only one level of content. However,

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:35.600
once you add depth to the menu, 
you'll run into accessibility issues.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:42.640
Let's take a look at how wp_nav_menu 
interprets each of the three cases I shared,

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:50.640
then we can see how we might improve their 
accessibility. The markup for a plain link

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:56.800
is pretty straightforward. WordPress gives us 
just what we need, an anchor tag with a URL.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:03.680
This will provide a nice accessible link that 
supports people who use keyboard navigation and

00:11:03.680 --> 00:11:10.400
or screen readers. So far so good. After 
this, things start to get complicated.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:19.600
In this case, we want to provide the ability 
to either click on a top-level link to visit

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:27.120
a page or access items in a sub-menu. As 
the markup is now though, we run into a

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:34.720
couple of things that could be better. First the 
aria-label attribute on the link takes precedence

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:42.480
for screen readers over the content inside of 
the anchor tag. So instead of a screen reader

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:49.280
saying the inner text of the link which is About 
Us, it will say the value of the aria-label which

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:55.840
is just sub-menu. That's not terribly descriptive, 
because someone might want to click the link.

00:11:57.280 --> 00:12:04.000
Next, aria-haspopup will announce to a 
screen reader that a pop-up is available,

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:11.200
but we're missing supporting ARIA attributes to 
associate the link with a specific sub-menu and

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:19.040
indicate if that sub-menu is open or closed. Last, 
depending on how the sub-menu is hidden and shown,

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:25.920
there might be no good way for people who use a 
keyboard to get to it effectively. In addition,

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:30.960
aside from showing the sub-menu when the mouse 
hovers over the list element, it's not clear how

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:36.080
we can open the sub-menu. If we click on the 
link it'll take us to the page and never open

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:44.000
the sub-menu. If we just want the top nav item to 
work as a toggle, we can use a hash symbol as the

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.800
link. Of course then we need to use JavaScript 
to prevent it from reloading the page when

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:53.680
the link is clicked and this is something that 
internally at our department we wanted to avoid.

00:12:54.720 --> 00:13:00.640
However, if we get rid of the href attribute 
by removing any link from the admin area,

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:06.480
the item can't be focused with a keyboard. 
Browsers will interpret anchor tags without an

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:13.360
href property like a span or any other inline 
element. So we can add non-JavaScript dependent

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:21.040
toggles to list of issues we need to handle. Now 
I'd like to show you uh what we'd like to add,

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:27.760
how we're going to get there, and what the result 
is. At this point, what I wanted was a portable,

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:34.160
flexible, robust set of choices to build 
off. That included things like being able

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:40.160
to distinguish between links that go somewhere 
and toggles that don't. More ARIA attributes

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:45.840
to support people who use screen readers, 
custom classes, icons and so and so on.

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:53.520
WordPress does provide some additional filters 
for navigation menus such as wp_nav_menu items,

00:13:53.520 --> 00:14:00.400
wp_nav_menu_object filters. However, I wanted 
to be able to create the same kinds of markup

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:06.000
across a variety of themes. For us, this 
would help with our brand consistency and

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:12.320
visitor expectation from one site to the next. 
Fortunately, we can tap into an override the

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:18.960
core class wp_nav_menu uses to generate the 
output for a navigation menu. We can do this

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:24.880
with a custom Walker class. To make it portable 
we can then turn that into a Composer package

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:30.480
that can be installed from GitHub or Packagist.
The project can then be used in many places.

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:38.880
The Walker_Nav_Menu class is part of a collection 
of Walkers which all inherit their functionality

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:45.600
from a general Walker class. Now to be completely 
honest, when I started looking into this back

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:51.920
then, the Walkers were incredibly confusing. 
Fortunately, these classes take care of a lot of

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:58.080
the work for us though. For example, we don't have 
to worry about writing our own recursive functions

00:14:58.080 --> 00:15:03.040
to traverse menu structure since that's 
their main purpose . Rather we can focus

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:07.840
on logic for the markup our menu might 
need and what the output should look like.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:14.080
Once you write your a custom 
Walker class you can then add it

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:16.880
to the list of arguments used by wp_nav_menu.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:22.240
When you do this, all the 
markup created by wp-nav-menu

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:28.080
will flow through the Custom Walker. This means 
that you can override any of the Walker nav

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:36.400
menu's methods, with your own and that's what 
wp_nav_menu will use. There are four class methods

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:41.840
available which will let you start a level, 
start an element, end an element and end a level.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:48.560
In this context, we only need two of those. 
The one to start a level and start an element.

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:57.680
Every item in the menu is going to pass through 
the start_el and end_el methods.These methods

00:15:58.240 --> 00:16:03.360
are where we can add logic to support 
the type of markup we want to build.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:09.280
Consequently, the start-el method was where 
most of the work for my Custom Walker happened.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:15.520
However, we're not just dealing with a flat 
menu, we need to be able to add depth as well.

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:23.440
When we create a nested sub-menu the 
Walker will pass the output for the markup

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:28.560
through the start and end level methods 
as well. These create the unordered lists.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:36.640
We can take advantage of that to affect how the 
submenu unordered list elements get created.

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:43.600
In terms of accessibility, we can make sure we're 
adding useful IDs to each level for example.

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:51.440
By default WordPress wasn't doing this, or at 
least I don't remember it doing it back when I

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:57.920
started this. It may do it now. This will let us 
match up the sub-menu to an aria-owns property

00:16:57.920 --> 00:17:04.880
in the items markup. Now that we've seen the 
path the markup takes through the Walker class,

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:08.880
let's zoom in to the start_el method 
where most of the logic happens.

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:16.000
Here I've written out some pseudo code to describe 
the flow through our custom start_el  method.

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:20.960
The shell of this is exactly what you 
would see if you took a look at the Walker.

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:28.240
We can start by checking to see if the current 
item has children. That is, should it be a link by

00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:35.120
itself, or should it have a sub-menu with it. If 
not, if it's just a link by itself, we can output

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:39.680
the start of a list item with 
a link inside and then finish.

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:46.880
Otherwise, we need to know if the top 
level item should be a link or a button.

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:54.720
If it doesn't have a link, we can output the 
start of a list item with a button on the inside.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:18:03.600
Otherwise, we need both a link and then a 
button as a sibling. This way we can account for

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:10.400
all the cases in the markup. With this logic in 
place we can also do things like add additional

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:16.800
custom classes and data attributes. Those can help 
us style and interact with the menu more easily.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.280
Let's look at some examples of the 
output that the Custom Walker I wrote,

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:31.280
creates. So here we're back at our plain 
link, but notice that we've added prefixed am

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:38.320
dash classes in addition to the standard WordPress 
classes. These will help designers and developers

00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:43.680
create styles specifically for these types of 
menus without relying on WordPress classes.

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:51.280
There's also a no.js class on the element. The 
no.js class will be removed from the markup

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:56.080
if the menu's JavaScript is available. 
If the JavaScript doesn't run,

00:18:56.080 --> 00:19:01.200
this class will provide a fail safe for opening 
and closing sub-menus as I'll show soon.

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:08.640
Here's how we can improve the markup 
for linked items with sub-menus.

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:16.480
First, instead of the link, links 
aria-label only saying sub-menu,

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:21.760
it now describes the text of the link and gives 
a hint about how you can interact with it.

00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:27.520
You can obviously change this to 
whatever is appropriate for you. Next,

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:34.240
the button is going to provide a semantically 
appropriate element that we can interact with

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:40.720
whether JavaScript is available or not. We've 
also added a couple more ARIA attributes to it.

00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:48.000
Aria-expanded will indicate to a screen 
reader if the sub-menu is open or not.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:55.520
We can change its state with JavaScript 
later. Since we don't want any text to

00:19:55.520 --> 00:20:01.680
show on the button, we need to give it an 
aria-label to provide context. If it's,

00:20:02.320 --> 00:20:08.240
this is in case the button is focused. Inside 
the button we can then make space for an icon.

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:16.080
Here we can use the aria-hidden property. The 
aria-hidden property will hide only the icon

00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:21.920
from screen readers, but still leave it visually 
available. Since we've created screen reader

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:28.800
accessible text on the button with the aria-label 
property and added the aria-expanded property,

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:37.200
we can use aria-hidden to hide the icon without a 
problem. The aria-owns property will associate the

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:44.320
button with the sub-menu that with the sub-menu 
with the aria-owns property or the correct ID

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:53.040
rather. This works in a way similar to how a label 
is associated with a form element. This is now

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:59.120
markup that will let a visitor choose between 
clicking on a link or opening up a sub-menu.

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:07.840
In the last case, there is no link for the item. 
It's replaced entirely by a button, so it can

00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:15.680
always act as a toggle. You can imagine that if 
you combine all these cases you can start to get

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:23.520
a very flexible and accessible menu, but we're 
not quite done yet. So far we've made sure that

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:29.840
people will be able to interact with the menu with 
a mouse, keyboard, keyboard and a screen reader,

00:21:30.560 --> 00:21:34.800
but now we have to think a little bit 
more about design and interaction.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:40.480
In our context, we wanted menus to 
work primarily through toggling action.

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:49.680
Actually, um as I was writing this, I forgot 
one thing and I added this slide today.

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:54.000
So as I was preparing the presentation 
I realized I had made a mistake.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:22:01.760
Uh, in the navigation menu you want to have the 
current, the current page and or its top level

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:08.480
parent visually highlighted somehow, and this lets 
people know which page is active. WordPress gives

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:14.880
classes for this, but also you want to make sure 
that the aria-current property is set on pages.

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:20.080
Prior to WordPress 5.3 I think, 
you had to do this manually.

00:22:20.720 --> 00:22:26.800
Typically, you could check the, you could do 
this with the nav_menu_link attributes filter,

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:32.640
but in checking, this filter doesn't seem to 
work with the custom Walker I created. I'm not

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:38.960
entirely sure why right now, so I'm going to have 
to go back and refine it, but that's okay. I think

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:44.400
the more important thing is to note that even 
while trying my best , I still ended up missing

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:48.960
something by accident, which is all the more 
reason for me to keep learning and researching.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:58.560
Now I'm not going to go over everything in the CSS 
for this project, but rather focus on CSS related

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:06.640
to hiding and showing content. When we use CSS 
to hide and show content, our choices affect how

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:14.640
people who use screen readers and keyboards can 
or cannot interact with web content. The ability

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:20.240
to show and hide content is an important part 
of user interface and user experience design.

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:26.880
This is especially true for navigation menus 
where we often want to hide or show content

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:33.280
on hover or focus. If we're not careful, 
we can inadvertently use CSS to create

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:38.480
an inaccessible experience for our visitors. 
So I think that it's important to understand

00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:43.360
the accessibility implications of 
how we use CSS to accomplish this.

00:23:44.720 --> 00:23:49.760
There's several cases where this chart is 
important. We might consider the case where a

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:55.840
visitor who uses a screen reader wants to skim all 
the links on a site. We should be aware that if

00:23:55.840 --> 00:24:02.800
we use display:none or visibility:hidden, we'll be 
hiding content from them. Another visitor may come

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:09.120
to our site and have an issue with motor control 
and browse with a keyboard. Depending on how we

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:16.320
hide and show content, our choices may make that 
user experience more or less accessible. If the

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:22.480
links in the navigation menu can be found in other 
ways or duplicated somewhere, that may not be a

00:24:22.480 --> 00:24:27.840
problem. But we should think about our choices and 
the overall context of the site as we make them.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.680
One of the design requirements as 
I've said for our menus, was that

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:39.840
some menus should be open and closed by toggle. 
The usual way to do this is with JavaScript,

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:43.760
so that when someone clicks on the menu 
item, the sub-menu is shown or hidden.

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:48.480
However, we can't predict if people 
will have JavaScript available to them.

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:54.000
Some people may choose to not use 
JavaScript. They may block it entirely.

00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:59.680
There may be a delay getting JavaScript 
to someone, or there may be an error that

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:05.920
prevents JavaScript from loading correctly. If 
we're going to hide the sub-menus or content,

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:11.040
we should still think about how we can 
give people a way to access those items.

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:17.280
One way to do this is the focus-within 
pseudo class which I'll describe in a moment.

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:21.360
You should be aware though, that focus-within

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:26.400
isn't supported by Internet Explorer or 
non-chromium versions of Microsoft Edge.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.720
According to the analytics 
I looked at for our sites,

00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:33.440
this represented a small 
percentage of our visitors.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:40.000
Further, this pseudo class will only be used 
in the event that JavaScript fails altogether.

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:48.160
I think that the browser restrictions are a 
fair trade-off to get a very similar effect. Now

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:56.160
if the JavaScript does not run correctly the no-js 
class and its styles will be applied to the menu.

00:25:56.160 --> 00:26:02.480
This includes the focus-within pseudo class. The 
Mozilla developer network says that focus-within,

00:26:03.840 --> 00:26:10.240
"represents an element that has received focus 
or contains an element that has received focus.

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:14.320
In other words, it represents an element that is

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:19.760
itself matched by the focus pseudo class or 
has a descendant that is matched by focus."

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:28.560
In plain terms, this means that even if a parent 
element can't be focused, if a child element can,

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:34.080
the entire structure can be styled 
as if the parent can be focused,

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:40.240
That's why it can be applied to the unordered 
list element, instead of an anchor tag.

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:47.760
Typically unordered list elements can't receive 
focus, but because the list can contain an

00:26:47.760 --> 00:26:53.440
element like a link that can receive focus, the 
list will respond to the focus-within class.

00:26:55.200 --> 00:27:01.360
Here's a small demonstration. The markup 
for each of these menus is exactly the same.

00:27:01.360 --> 00:27:07.520
You can confirm as much by going to the CodePen 
linked in the slide. The only difference

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:15.360
is the use of the focus-within selector. You 
can see that on the left, the sub menu elements

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:21.920
for the About Us menu item aren't 
reachable by keyboard. However,

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:26.320
on the right you can tab through them 
as you would the top level links.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:33.840
Here is an example in context. The 
Admissions and About elements are

00:27:33.840 --> 00:27:39.680
links with buttons to toggle sub-menus next to 
them as siblings, symbolized by the carrots.

00:27:40.800 --> 00:27:46.960
Without JavaScript enabled, you can see 
how a visitor might traverse the menu items

00:27:46.960 --> 00:27:51.600
just with a keyboard and of course, 
they can still use a mouse as well.

00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:58.320
There are still some improvements we can make 
to this though. For instance, maybe a visitor

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:03.840
doesn't want to tab through every single item of 
every single sub-menu to find the one they want.

00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:10.000
In this menu, maybe they want to tab to the 
student life sub-menu without going through

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:18.720
all the others. Now for that we need to start 
talking about JavaScript. We can definitely get

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:25.200
some accessibility improvements to this type 
of menu if we add JavaScript. In this project

00:28:25.200 --> 00:28:31.360
when a button is clicked the aria-expanded 
state changes from true to false or vice versa.

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:37.840
The CSS is then set up so that the button's 
icon will be changed depending on the state.

00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:44.800
This provides both visual and auditory context 
for sites visitors as they use the menu.

00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:52.960
However, one group that we haven't really 
talked about is developers themselves. We

00:28:52.960 --> 00:28:58.320
might create a plug-in or library that 
has technically excellent accessibility,

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:02.560
but if it's hard for a developer who's 
beginning their career to use the JavaScript

00:29:02.560 --> 00:29:07.360
or CSS that's included, they may choose 
to avoid using the project altogether.

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:15.280
The JavaScript or CSS for that matter, for 
this project, doesn't require any additional

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:22.560
dependencies or libraries. Not only that, but 
in the context of WordPress the relevant script

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:30.480
or styles can be enqueued directly from Composer's 
vendor directory. This means that developers don't

00:29:30.480 --> 00:29:36.960
need any additional front-end tooling or bundling 
libraries to get started. All that's required,

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:41.360
is that they follow a typical WordPress 
workflow to enqueue dependencies.

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:49.760
Once the script is properly enqueued 
it also has a very small external API.

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:56.160
There's a configuration object which only has 
two properties, both of which are optional.

00:29:57.120 --> 00:30:03.600
In order to use the navigation JavaScript, there's 
only one method you need to know. This means

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:09.600
developers with a wide range of experience can 
use this in their projects. This approach may be

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:15.680
less flexible than something with a larger API. 
However, I believe in this context it's a good

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:20.880
trade-off, because developers with a wide range 
of experience will be able to use it more quickly.

00:30:21.600 --> 00:30:27.760
In fact, as a university, sometimes we have 
student developers who work on our projects.

00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:34.880
The init method in the JavaScript starts by 
defining which menu the JavaScript should

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:43.920
apply to. It then removes the Node.js CSS class 
from that menu. Finally, it runs a method to

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:48.880
setEventListeners on the menu and the 
document. The setEventListeners method

00:30:48.880 --> 00:30:54.880
attaches listeners to menu items and prepares 
them to pass events to an eventDispatcher.

00:30:55.840 --> 00:31:01.360
The dispatcher determines the type of event 
and routes it to a particular eventHandler.

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:06.960
Once the event is properly dispatched 
to the handler, it's responsible

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:10.080
for the logic to set the state 
of menu items and properties.

00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:16.160
Depending on the state of the menu, 
eventListeners are also added to the document,

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:21.920
so people can close open sub-menus, with the 
escape key or by clicking outside the menu area.

00:31:24.240 --> 00:31:29.760
Here are two of the event handlers that are part 
of the JavaScript. They're divided so that they

00:31:29.760 --> 00:31:36.160
can manage mouse or focus events separately. And
while I was working on the project, I found it was

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:41.760
best to keep mouse, keyboard, and focus events 
separate from each other. That way I could

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:47.440
handle exceptions for each type of event while 
encapsulating other parts of the code for reuse.

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:55.120
One thing to note here, is that these menu 
follow the disclosure design pattern for

00:31:55.120 --> 00:32:01.280
navigation menus. As I understand it, in terms 
of keyboard support, this means that they're

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:08.480
required to do three things. Move among items 
with the Tab key, be able to select and activate

00:32:08.480 --> 00:32:13.840
items once they're focused with the Space or 
Enter key and close items with the Escape key.

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:22.080
This is very different than an element with the 
Menu ARIA role. The Menu ARIA Role requires more

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:29.200
types of keyboard interaction, such as the ability 
to use arrow keys. However, in the example linked

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:34.000
in the slide, well it doesn't appear to be linked 
in the slide, sorry about that. We'll get that

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:42.160
later. Uh the markup is trying to create something 
more like an application menu for a text editor.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:46.880
If it turns out that I'm completely wrong about 
this, and that I need to add more keyboard support

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:52.640
to the menus, that's okay. The JavaScript is 
flexible enough to allow more types of keyboard

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:58.880
events. The event routing would require only 
a few additional cases. From there I could add

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:04.720
appropriate event handlers without too much 
difficulty, I hope. In any event, I think

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:10.320
it's always worth going back to review projects 
from the past and see how they can be updated.

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:15.920
Earlier this morning I read an article 
about WCAG 2.2 and for all I know I'll need

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:20.400
to bring this project up to date to conform 
at some point to that, or a future version.

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:28.400
In any event, here you can see the effect 
the JavaScript has on keyboard navigation. A

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:33.840
visitor can now select among different sub-menus, 
however they like, with a mouse or a keyboard.

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:40.560
Once the sub-menu is open, the next key press on 
the tab key will take visitors to the sub-menu.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:47.440
You can also see the relevant icon stays changed 
as well, until someone leaves and closes the menu.

00:33:48.880 --> 00:33:53.120
This is done by tying the CSS to the 
aria-expanded attribute of the toggle.

00:33:55.200 --> 00:34:01.360
Here are just a few resources collected into one 
